Brazilian Stock Movers: Cyrela, Gafisa, Gol, Rossi, Tam

-- B y   A l e x a n d e r   C u a d r o s
-- 
2011-08-12T20:31:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-12/brazilian-stock-movers-cyrela-gafisa-gol-rossi-tam.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Sao Paulo trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4:15 p.m. New York time.
Preferred shares are usually the most-traded class of stock.  The Bovespa Index rose 0.2 percent to 53,473.35.  Gol Linhas Aereas Inteligentes SA (GOLL4)  (GOLL4 BS) slipped 1.6
percent to 10.18 reais.  Brazil ’s second-biggest airline by
market value said losses widened in the second quarter as fuel
costs surged and sales dropped. The net loss expanded to 358.7
million reais in the three months ended June 30, from 51.9
million reais a year earlier, Sao Paulo-based Gol said in a
statement yesterday. The stock has fallen 59 percent this year.
Gol is not considering delisting the company, Chief Executive
Officer Constantino de Oliveira Jr. said in a conference call
with analysts today.  Homebuilders  Rossi Residencial SA (RSID3)  (RSID3 BS) fell 6.1
percent to 10.66 reais,  Cyrela Brazil Realty SA Empreendimentos
e Participacoes (CYRE3)  (CYRE3 BS) lost 5.7 percent to 13.83 reais, and
 Gafisa SA (GFSA3)  (GFSA3 BS) slipped 6 percent to 6.91 reais. Rossi’s
second-quarter net income fell 19 percent from a year earlier to
85 million reais, Cyrela’s dropped 43 percent to 95.9 million
reais and Gafisa’s plunged 74 percent to 25.1 million reais,
according to filings from the companies. That compares to
estimates by JPMorgan Chase & Co. for profits of 92 million
reais, 117 million reais and 50 million reais, respectively.  Tam SA (TAMM4)  (TAMM4 BS) rallied 5.8 percent to 29.28 reais. Lan
Airlines SA’s pending takeover of the Brazilian carrier was
recommended for “approval without restrictions” by Brazil’s
 Finance Ministry . SEAE, as the Finance Ministry body in charge
of analyzing possible mergers and acquisitions in Brazil is
known, will now send its report to the country’s antitrust
agency, which will make a final decision.  To contact the reporter on this story:
